          <td bgcolor="" valign="top" width="1"><img src="/magination/gfx/trans_header1.gif" width="22" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chblue"><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/treports/treports.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Aurora, CO 03/09/2002<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=9173'>Nathan "Rex" Reed</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=9173&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 12, 2002</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Sealed Deck Report,<br>
Well I shall bravely enter the undisturbed waters of a sealed deck tournament report for Magi Nation here, knowing full well what happened last time I did such an act (Me Hopes no one with Poisonous touch reviews this).<br>
<br>
First the rules present that impacted the playing field:<br>
Decks were selected by the participants when they signed up, they could select any available region and would get 2 boosters from the same release.  Decks were then put into the pool.  Once all participants were registered, decks were randomly assigned to players.<br>
<br>
Core Decks:  Core decks had Regional Restrictions changed to Regional Penalties, but only for Core Magi, not the other way around.<br>
<br>
3 Card limit: Out the window.<br>
<br>
Still was a 40 card minimum and no duplication of magi.<br>
<br>
Well the Deck assignment phase went well and the results were rather surprising.  First our group is very much in the &#39;if<br>
you wont, I wont&#39; state of mind, once everyone saw how powerful Core could be in a sealed deck tournament the general consensus was, if you don&#39;t pick it, I wont pick it.  I think most did not want an opposing deck to get such a starting advantage.<br>
<br>
With that said, every other region was represented, and we discovered what has been said about how each region is primarily tested against those of the same release (IE Naroom is balanced against all of the other unlimited decks, where as Kybars and Weave are balanced against each other).  In the end KT and Weave just owned the other regions in a sealed deck environment and the finale it was those two duking it out for first and second.  The Unlimited decks were always close matches against each other (well with the exception of the Orothe Deck, that deck just fell apart. Terrible cards in the booster forced that deck to really &#39;splash&#39; in a lot of other regions), but they crumbled under the might of Dreams End.<br>
<br>
Now the Battle Reports<br>
Air vs. Rock <br>
First I was to represent Arderial in this tournament environment, and my first opponent was Kybars Teeth, the only one present.  The KT player lucked out, in one booster was Ullig and in the other was Ulligs slingshot, and Ullig lead the charge.  My creatures crashed against her time and again but the slingshot combined with their Invulnerability it was just as effective as a summer breeze against the granite walls of the Rockies.  Lassada fell rather quickly bringing in the Adept Shimmer, I made a huge creature ready to pound some of that Kybar mountain to dust, but a pair of Jagged Rocks just cut me down to size and made for an easy defeat of Shimmer.  Then out came Stradus, his effect countering Invulnerability, at least when they attacked, still it was too late for my Air-force and I fell to the might of Ullig.  Not once did I get to damage her, and the one time I got through her wall of critters, she got that 4e and I could not bring her down.<br>
<br>
Bye- Aye I got the bye.<br>
I watched the other matches and made some observations, the KT and Weave Decks dominated their foes while the matches between the Unlimited decks seemed to be pretty close.  Naroom and Underneath being very strong in this area-Naroom with good magi and some big critters where Underneath had Warriors boots and Gogor (AKA The Death Machine) (thank goodness base set doesn&#39;t come with Pylofufs).  The only real bad deck was Orothe, their magi effects never used and just not enough energy advantage to get a leg/fin up.<br>
<br>
Air vs. Air<br>
My last match was against another air, but he had gotten lucky and obtained an Adis in his boosters, so at least he wasn&#39;t stuck with Shimmer, but he made an error in deck design and went Adis, Stradus, and Lasada.  Since magi order is fixed he only realized his error after his second match.  This one was close but what it came down to was I got my Collusus out first and he never got his out.  Having to crash himselainst that behemoth gained me the critical opening I needed to get both his first and second magi.  Lassada fell but Shimmer learned her lesson against the rocks and spread the energy evenly over her forces only to use the Cloud Narth and Pharan to build a massive Xyx Minor once the opportunity presented itself.  Fog banks and Eclipses helped in delaying immediate demises but in the end he was unable to get his last shockwave before Xyx Minor finished him off.<br>
<br>
Well in the end, Kybars Teeth took first, Weave took second, and Naroom took third, with Underneath and Cald in close running.<br>
<br>
In the end I think the psuedo-random works very well it keeps the players acting in a &#39;fair&#39; manner while still choosing the fate of the tournament.<br>
<br>
Comments heard while playing:<br>
&#39;This was fun, even though I got abused!&#39;-Orothe Player<br>
&#39;I never play this region and after today I still wont.&#39;-Cald Player who is used to playing Arderial only.<br>
&#39;Hey, think of it this way, I finally won once against you.&#39;-Weave Player to someone who has dominated many constructed tournaments.<br>
&#39;BWAHAHAHAHAHA!!&#39;-Naroom Player who played 3 grows on his Forest Hyren and rolled a 6, a 5, and a 5.<br>
&#39;HA!&#39;-Underneath player who used a Shockwave (yes, he splashed one in) on previously noted Forest Hyren.<br>
<br>
Those who were used to winning with constructed decks found themselves fighting for their lives. And those who had only ever played one region found that while mastery of one does not mean mastery of all.<br>
<br>
All in all everyone had a good time and I look forward to running the next one.<br>
<br>
